3.3.2 SDS-PEO Interaction in Water-IL-Mixed Solvents 

Isothermal titration calorimetry has been extensively used in studies of polymer–

surfactant interactions because it helps researchers obtain important parameters that 

characterize this kind of interaction, such as the cac, C2, the integral enthalpy change for 

aggregate formation [? ], the standard free energy of micelle adsorption on the 
macromolecule chain (?? ), and the extent of binding of the surfactant to the 
polymer.2,7 By using ITC in mixed systems containing water, IL, SDS, and PEO, we can 

evaluate the effect of ILs on these aggregation parameters for PEO-SDS interactions. 

Figure 3.6 presents the ITC curves obtained by titrating a 472.0 mM SDS solution 

