Numbers on the curves give the surfactant concentrations. 



Similarly to the SDS effect on the Lf thermograms, DSS and SDBS promote 

changes on the area and the position of the endothermic peaks, showing that both 

surfactants also interact with Lf promoting its denaturation. However, different surfactant 

concentrations are necessary to denaturate completely the Lf, indicating that the  

Lf-surfactant binding constant depends on the surfactant structure. When the surfactant 

is the DSS, the first endothermic peak disappears at 5.0 mM while the peak associated 

with the second thermal transition is not observed from 8.0 mM. On the other hand, when 

SDBS is present, the first and second peaks disappear at 0.75 mM and 1.0 mM, 

